tish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"St","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  French: habitational name from any of the places so called, for example in Normandy, named from a religious dedication to a (male) St. Clair.","2  North American variant spelling of   St  .   Claire  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Claire","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Clare  .","Variant of   Clair  , an altered form of German   Klare  .","French: variant of   Clair  ."]}]},{"name":"Valery","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Colette, Pierre, Raoul, Yva.","French and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the personal name <i>Valery</i>, French form of Latin <i>Valerius</i> (see   Valerio  ).","Americanized form of Italian   Valerio   or   Valeri  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vallery","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Leonce, Monique.","French:","habitational name from Vallery in Yonne, once a Gallo-Roman estate, recorded in 1218 as <i>Valerianus</i>."]},{"name":"Valerio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Ana, Manuel, Pedro, Mario, Luis, Francisco, Ramon, Ruben, Carlos, Jesus.  Italian Antonio, Angelo, Lucio, Francesco, Maurizio, Niccolo, Romeo, Vito, Amadeo, Anastasio, Aureliano, Carmela.","Spanish and Italian: from the personal name <i>Valerio</i>, from Latin <i>Valerius</i>, a Roman surname ultimately derived from Latin <i>valere</i> ‘to flourish, to be strong and healthy’. The name was borne by several early Christian saints, among them 4th-century bishops of Trier and Zaragoza and 5th-century bishops of Sorrento and of Antibes. Compare   Valery  ."]}]},{"name":"Bernard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>ber(n)</i> ‘bear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. This was the name of three famous medieval churchmen:  St Bernard  of Menthon (  923–1008 ), founder of a hospice on each of the Alpine passes named after him; the monastic reformer  St Bernard  of Clairvaux (  1090–1153 ); and the scholastic philosopher  Bernard  of Chartres. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England. A native Old English form, <i>Beornheard</i>, was superseded by the Norman form."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Bernard de St Valery 1v was born in 1113, in London, England. He married Matilda Aleanore De Dommart. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1191, in England, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1113–1191":"1113–1191","1119–1178":"1119–1178","1142–1219":"1142–1219","1113":"1113","1178":"1178","1142":"1142","1219":"1219","1191":"1191","1119":"1119","England":"England","London, England":"London, England","Wittingham, Surrey, England":"Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1113–1191":"1113–1191","1119–1178":"1119–1178","1142–1219":"1142–1219","1113":"1113","1178":"1178","1142":"1142","1219":"1219","1191":"1191","1119":"1119","England":"England","London, England":"London, England","Wittingham, Surrey, England":"Surrey, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1113–1191":"1113–1191","1119–1178":"1119–1178","1142–1219":"1142–1219","1113":"1113","1178":"1178","1142":"1142","1219":"1219","1191":"1191","1119":"1119","England":"Angleterre","London, England":"Londres, Angleterre","Wittingham, Surrey, England":"Surrey, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Bernard de St Valery 1v est né en 1113, à Londres, Angleterre. Il a épousé Matilda Aleanore De Dommart. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1191, à Angleterre, à l’âge de 78 ans."},"de":{"1113–1191":"11